    "created_at": "2017-05-24T14:01:12Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-24T14:01:12Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I'm not sure there's a 100% reliable way to tell what version of pip is running the installation (`import pip` might get you a different version to the one in use), so I would be a bit wary of trying to be clever with detecting the version.\r\n\r\n> There is still pip 1.6 around because that's what ubuntu 16.04 LTS has\r\n\r\nNo, 16.04 has pip 8 by default, and that's new enough to warn you that newer versions are available. 14.04, which is still supported, has pip 1.5 if users haven't got a newer version from another source. You can check info like this on the web:\r\nhttps://packages.ubuntu.com/search?keywords=python3-pip&searchon=names&suite=all&section=all"
  }
